All the samples were characterized by X-ray diffraction (XRD) patterns, which were recorded with sample rotation on an HZG-4 (Ni filter) diffractometer: CuKα radiation in the diffracted beam, stepwise mode (counting time 10 s, a step of 0.02°). Qualitative XRD phase analyses were carried out using JCPDS PDF-2 and literature data. The sizes of coherent scattering regions (L, Å) were evaluated using the Scherrer formula:L=0.9λ/βcosθ,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$L = 0.9\lambda /\beta \cos \theta ,$$\end{document}where β is the measured integral breadth of the peak (2θ ~ 25°).

The average sizes of particles were calculated according to formula:N=Kp(ρA),\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$N = Kp(\rho A),$$\end{document}where N is the average size of the particles; Kp is the shape factor of the particles (6 for cubes and spheres, 4 for prisms and round rods, 2 for plates); ρ is the density of the material (ρ = 3.84 g/cm3); and A is the specific surface area of the material.

The photocatalytic destruction of the MeO dye and salicylic acid can be described by the first-order kinetic model, lnc0/c=kt,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\ln \left( {c_{0} /c} \right) = kt,$$\end{document} where c0 is the initial concentration and c is the concentration at time t (Brown and Darwent 1984). Uncertainties in determining rate constants were ~10 %.
